KW  - S-LCA
KW  - Mobility
KW  - Case study
KW  - Use phase
KW  - Equality
KW  - Consumers
AB  - To mitigate climate change, many countries have plans for significantly reducing transportation-related greenhouse gas emissions, and various national and international policies have been implemented for this reason. Current practices, including such policies, may not treat citizens with different socioeconomic backgrounds equally. Previous research shows that, for example, people with low income have less access to electric vehicle charging infrastructure. This article studies how different citizen groups are affected by current mobility policy in Finland in terms of satisfaction, accessibility, and affordability. Considered policies are investment support for charging infrastructure and biofuel distribution obligation. Citizens are grouped based on transportation mode, income level, and residential area. The study was conducted using social life cycle assessment, and a reference scale method was used. Six new qualitative indicators are defined, and two quantitative indicators are modified from previous research. Data were acquired via a survey. The indicators reveal inequal social impacts within the citizen groups. Owners of electric vehicles were most satisfied regarding costs and comfort, and they had lower transportation costs than internal combustion engine car owners. People in the lowest income group were the least satisfied, they had the lowest accessibility to charging infrastructure in their homes, and the increase of fuel price had impacted them the most. The findings indicate that social life cycle assessment can be used to assess the social impacts of policies even though these impacts cannot be fully separated from other factors influencing mobility.
